            . I am a <rs id="t18080406-95-viclabel542" type="occupation">smith</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18080406-95-victim907 t18080406-95-viclabel542"></join> at Clapton.</p>
               <p>Q. Did you lose an iron axletree at any time - A. Yes; on the night of the 14th of March, or the morning of the 15th; it was upon a truck at the door.</p>
               <p>Q. Do you generally leave the things out all night - A. Yes; it was left out there for seven years almost. I afterwards saw the axletree at Worship-street office.</p>
               <p>Q. Do you know the prisoner - A. Yes: some years back he worked for me.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18080406-95-person909">
                  WILLIAM 
                  BROWN
               <interp inst="t18080406-95-person909" type="surname" value="BROWN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18080406-95-person909" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18080406-95-person909" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I work in the brick fields near Hackney. On the 15th March, between five and six o'clock in the morning, I saw the prisoner with this axletree and a wrench; I asked him where he was going with it; he said what was that to me; he was going to mend it; I clapped my hand against it, I told him I thought it did not want mending. I detained him; I delivered him to Mr. Griffiths.</p>
               <p>The property produced and identified</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. What that man said is all true.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18080406-95-verdict543" type="verdictDescription">
